response:
```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    // Block definitions
    Potentiometer -> Buffer -> LowPassFilter -> Attenuator -> AntiAliasingFilter -> DAQ;

    // Additional details
    Attenuator -> VoltageLimiter [label="to prevent overvoltage"];
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: The potentiometer, with a resistance of 10 kOhms, is the primary sensor for angle measurement. As the pendulum swings, the potentiometerâ€™s wiper moves, causing a change in the resistance which in turn changes the voltage across the wiper. This voltage is proportional to the angle of the pendulum.

Buffer: This is an operational amplifier configured as a voltage follower. It serves to provide a low impedance output from the high impedance potentiometer wiper, thus preventing loading effects and ensuring accurate voltage readings in relation to the pendulum's position.

LowPassFilter: A low-pass filter is utilized to attenuate unwanted high-frequency noise as well as specific frequencies that can interfere with the signal, such as 50 and 60 Hz from power line interference. The cutoff frequency of this filter will be set below those frequencies to ensure they are significantly reduced.

Attenuator: The attenuator is required to scale down the signal to a voltage range that is acceptable for the DAQ system. Since the DAQ can handle a maximum of +/-7V and the potentiometer is powered by a source between -10V and 10V, the attenuator will bring the voltage within the required range. Moreover, the attenuator block includes a voltage limiter to prevent any overvoltage situation which could potentially damage the DAQ.

AntiAliasingFilter: Before the signal is digitized by the DAQ, an anti-aliasing filter is necessary to further clean up the signal from any high-frequency components that could cause aliasing when sampled. The cut-off frequency of this filter will be just below half the sampling rate of the DAQ (Nyquist rate) to adhere to the sampling theorem.

DAQ: The Data Acquisition (DAQ) system is where the analog signal is converted into a digital signal which can then be processed, displayed, or recorded. The DAQ should have its own internal analog-to-digital converter (ADC) which will perform the digitization of the conditioned analog signal.
```

